replies.bodyText:
The default functionality, without IF NOT EXISTS would be to fail if a connector with the same name already exists.  (I'm assuming the Connect API would return some kind of 'already exists' error). Adding the IF NOT EXISTS syntax should mean it does NOT fail if the connector exists, instead it should be a no-op.  Hence the logic should be:
void create(...) {

   if (stmt.ifNotExists() && connectorExists(stmt.connectorName()) {
      // Connector exists already:
      return;
   }

   addConnector(stmt);
}
Of course, this would suffer from a race condition: the connector could be added by another system between the connectorExists check and the addConnector call.  So really, we also need the addConnector call to gracefully handle the already exists error we get back from the Connect client, and if we're handling than, is there really any point in the connectExists call?   Hence the code could just be:
void create(...) {
   final ConnectResponse<ConnectorInfo> response = client.create(...);
   if (response.datum().isPresent()) {
      return success(...);
   }

   if (stmt.ifNotExists()) {
      // somehow determine if the error was because the connector already existed with that name
      // hopefully this is possible by looking at the http status code, maybe its 409. Not sure.
      // Otherwise, we'd have to search the error message, which is brittle and we'd need an integration
      // test to ensure changes to Connect error message don't break this: 
      if (isAlreadyExisttsError(response)) {
         return alreadyExists(...);
      }
   }

   return response.error() 
        .map(err -> new ErrorEntity(statement.getStatementText(), err));	        .map(err -> new ErrorEntity(statement.getStatementText(), err));
Note, that's just pseudo code. I've no idea what the client does if the connector already exists.
Note2:it might help if the method isNotExists was renamed to onlyIfNotExists or ifNotExists or reversed and named ignoreIfExists, as isNotExists is .... confusing... at least to me.

